Not him, but if you are over thirty, it may take longer.

My workout, which is helping somewhat, but not working miracles is:

Monday, Wednesday, Friday: 90 minutes lifting weights

Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday: cardio, currently in the form of twelve miles on a stationary bicycle, which I can now do in under 40 minutes and occasionally under 37 but not yet under 36.

The doctors have me on a prescription appetite suppressant and that, combined with the exercise, has me losing 5-10 pounds per month. I have a long way to go and not every day is easy. I am eating a lot of sugar-free, fat-free yogurt type products, sometimes with whey protein powder stirred into them. Breakfast may be high fiber cereal with skim milk, and an apple, normally I don't eat lunch, and dinner tonight will be baked chicken and frozen vegetables, no bread, no pasta, no rice, and no dessert. I am trying to cut as much sugar and starch out of my diet as I can and reduce the amount of fat I eat. You can do this, but you have to stick with it for the long haul. And there are people who say "anybody can become Olympic athlete level fit in six months if you buy my book," but I think you may already know that isn't realistic for most people. It is a journey to being a better version of yourself and it will be the work of a lifetime, not "six months." And it's not something you do for others. You do it for you.
